1
00:00:02,232 --> 00:00:10,573
♪♪

2
00:00:10,573 --> 00:00:13,159
Mirren:
The natural world.

3
00:00:13,159 --> 00:00:15,411
Stunning in its beauty.

4
00:00:15,411 --> 00:00:18,915
♪♪

5
00:00:18,915 --> 00:00:21,543
Staggering in its complexity.

6
00:00:21,543 --> 00:00:27,215
♪♪

7
00:00:27,215 --> 00:00:29,300
And although these landscapes,

8
00:00:29,300 --> 00:00:32,303
with their myriad
of wild denizens,

9
00:00:32,303 --> 00:00:36,057
may seem alien at first...

10
00:00:36,057 --> 00:00:41,437
if we look closer,
relatable truths are revealed.

11
00:00:41,437 --> 00:00:44,274
For within this grandeur

12
00:00:44,274 --> 00:00:48,069
resides a wealth
of unexpected drama...

13
00:00:48,069 --> 00:00:49,487
Leopard:
Hey, stripe‐y!

14
00:00:49,487 --> 00:00:50,989
Zebra: Uh, yeah?

15
00:00:50,989 --> 00:00:53,700
I'm gonna mess you up.
Wahhh!

16
00:00:53,700 --> 00:00:54,784
[ Branch cracks, thud ]

17
00:00:54,784 --> 00:00:57,203
[ Cackling ]

18
00:00:57,203 --> 00:00:59,372
We are now empowered

19
00:00:59,372 --> 00:01:02,917
to explore
this once mysterious world

20
00:01:02,917 --> 00:01:06,462
and revel in the entirety
of life on this planet,

21
00:01:06,462 --> 00:01:09,716
an astonishing diversity
of beings

22
00:01:09,716 --> 00:01:13,344
each with their own
fascinating story.

23
00:01:13,344 --> 00:01:15,680
Gorilla #1: Jack,
I want you to draw me

24
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:17,682
like one of
your French girls.

25
00:01:17,682 --> 00:01:19,058
Wearing fleas.

26
00:01:19,058 --> 00:01:20,935
Gorilla #2:
All right.

27
00:01:20,935 --> 00:01:23,521
Wearing <i>only</i> fleas.

28
00:01:23,521 --> 00:01:26,065
Let us venture
beyond the protective canopy

29
00:01:26,065 --> 00:01:28,151
of Earth's forests...

30
00:01:28,151 --> 00:01:31,446
dive deep beneath
its roaring seas...

31
00:01:31,446 --> 00:01:35,325
traverse its austere
desert landscapes...

32
00:01:35,325 --> 00:01:37,535
and commune
with fellow travelers

33
00:01:37,535 --> 00:01:40,246
on this, our shared home.

34
00:01:40,246 --> 00:01:43,875
Baboon: Errrr....
I don't know about this.

35
00:01:43,875 --> 00:01:49,714
These animals ‐‐
vibrant, diverse, passionate ‐‐

36
00:01:49,714 --> 00:01:52,175
are not so different from us.

37
00:01:52,175 --> 00:01:54,969
And if we listened
close enough...

38
00:01:54,969 --> 00:01:58,765
what would we hear
these noble creatures say?

39
00:01:58,765 --> 00:02:03,770
Turtle: I don't want
to be on reality TV!!

40
00:02:03,770 --> 00:02:06,022
Ohh! Ugh! Ugh!

41
00:02:06,022 --> 00:02:07,607
[ Birds calling ]

42
00:02:07,607 --> 00:02:11,986
Prepare yourself
for a truly unique journey...

43
00:02:11,986 --> 00:02:16,157
and witness the beauty and
wonder that can transpire...

44
00:02:18,701 --> 00:02:20,828
♪♪

45
00:02:20,828 --> 00:02:23,873
[ Wind whistling ]

46
00:02:23,873 --> 00:02:25,583
Male stork:
No, no, that's not right.

47
00:02:25,583 --> 00:02:28,419
I said it's hit, boom, turn,

48
00:02:28,419 --> 00:02:30,463
then shimmy,
whack‐a‐mole, whack‐a‐mole,

49
00:02:30,463 --> 00:02:33,091
then boom, unh,
carrot stick, pop.

50
00:02:33,091 --> 00:02:35,927
Lean with it. Rock with it.

51
00:02:35,927 --> 00:02:38,179
Scoop, cat‐cat, then turn.

52
00:02:38,179 --> 00:02:40,014
Giraffe neck.
Eat the leaves from the tree.

53
00:02:40,014 --> 00:02:41,891
Eat the leaves from the tree.

54
00:02:41,891 --> 00:02:44,686
Then you stand on one leg.
Got it?

55
00:02:44,686 --> 00:02:46,354
Stork: No.
Again.

56
00:02:46,354 --> 00:02:52,151
♪♪

57
00:02:52,151 --> 00:02:58,282
♪♪

58
00:02:58,282 --> 00:03:04,038
Mirren: The animal kingdom stirs
with wonder and possibility.

59
00:03:04,038 --> 00:03:07,875
It is the very tapestry
of creation itself.

60
00:03:07,875 --> 00:03:09,877
♪♪

61
00:03:09,877 --> 00:03:12,714
Join me as we experience

62
00:03:12,714 --> 00:03:16,676
this majestic orb
in a new light.

63
00:03:16,676 --> 00:03:18,928
I'm Helen Mirren.

64
00:03:18,928 --> 00:03:20,638
Yeah, <i>that</i> Helen Mirren.

65
00:03:20,638 --> 00:03:22,473
Legend of the stage and screen,

66
00:03:22,473 --> 00:03:24,475
winner of an Oscar,
four Emmys, one Tony,

67
00:03:24,475 --> 00:03:27,103
four BAFTAs, which is like
the British version

68
00:03:27,103 --> 00:03:29,605
of the MTV Movie Awards.

69
00:03:29,605 --> 00:03:32,859
But, you know, let's not make
a whole thing out of it.

70
00:03:32,859 --> 00:03:37,447
I'm ‐‐ I'm just a regular dame
like you.

71
00:03:37,447 --> 00:03:40,700
Our journey will touch upon
the commonalities

72
00:03:40,700 --> 00:03:45,872
that we, as humans, share
with our brethren in the wild.

73
00:03:45,872 --> 00:03:49,333
We all, animal and human alike,

74
00:03:49,333 --> 00:03:52,420
live and work and love,

75
00:03:52,420 --> 00:03:55,631
and, sometimes,
we don't wear pants.

76
00:03:58,759 --> 00:04:02,930
Tonight, we will focus on what
we learn from our experiences,

77
00:04:02,930 --> 00:04:06,642
how we grow, the life lessons.

78
00:04:06,642 --> 00:04:11,564
Chief among these is how
we master our environment.

79
00:04:11,564 --> 00:04:15,276
And in the forests of Brazil,
there is no greater example

80
00:04:15,276 --> 00:04:19,197
than the crafty, tufted
capuchin monkey.

81
00:04:20,615 --> 00:04:22,283
Dad monkey: Okay.
Gonna fix the HVAC.

82
00:04:22,283 --> 00:04:25,328
Easy. Very easy.
Mr. Fix‐It, that's me.

83
00:04:25,328 --> 00:04:27,205
Is this thing ‐‐
Is this thing hollow?

84
00:04:27,205 --> 00:04:29,332
Is this supposed to, uh ‐‐
Maybe if I...

85
00:04:29,332 --> 00:04:31,292
Whoa.
Shhhh‐ish kebab!

86
00:04:31,292 --> 00:04:33,544
Dang it! That is not
supposed to come off.

87
00:04:33,544 --> 00:04:35,630
Mom monkey: Don, honey,
I do believe you can fix it,

88
00:04:35,630 --> 00:04:38,007
but it might be faster
to call a handyman.

89
00:04:38,007 --> 00:04:39,592
Oh, t‐there's
no need, honey.

90
00:04:39,592 --> 00:04:41,469
W‐We just have a problem
with one of these, uh,

91
00:04:41,469 --> 00:04:43,387
springy dealies.
You gotta roll it out.

92
00:04:43,387 --> 00:04:45,807
Handyman?
<i>I'm</i> a handyman.

93
00:04:45,807 --> 00:04:47,308
I'm a man. I have hands.

94
00:04:47,308 --> 00:04:49,060
This'll do the trick.
Just gotta...

95
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:50,812
This guy here,
stick this into the, uh ‐‐

96
00:04:50,812 --> 00:04:53,397
Fuuuuudge brownies.

97
00:04:53,397 --> 00:04:54,732
[ Exhales sharply ]
Keep it together, Don.

98
00:04:54,732 --> 00:04:56,275
Gah. Come on!
Maybe if I just...

99
00:04:56,275 --> 00:04:57,610
[ Grunting ]

100
00:04:57,610 --> 00:04:59,111
Don't know what I'm doing here.

101
00:04:59,111 --> 00:05:00,488
Maybe I need a Phillips head?

102
00:05:00,488 --> 00:05:03,282
Hey, honey! Can you
bring me the Phillips head?!

103
00:05:03,282 --> 00:05:05,201
That <i>was</i>
the Phillips head!

104
00:05:05,201 --> 00:05:07,912
I know! And now I need
a <i>flat</i> Phillips head.

105
00:05:07,912 --> 00:05:09,205
That's not a thing, Don.

106
00:05:09,205 --> 00:05:10,623
Kid monkey:
Want me to find you

107
00:05:10,623 --> 00:05:12,291
a YouTube tutorial, Dad?!

108
00:05:12,291 --> 00:05:14,418
A tutorial?!
A‐Absolutely not!

109
00:05:14,418 --> 00:05:16,796
I‐In fact, son,
you should come down here,

110
00:05:16,796 --> 00:05:19,465
learn a thing or two.
It's a good teachable moment.

111
00:05:19,465 --> 00:05:21,259
What am I talking about,
"teachable moment"?

112
00:05:21,259 --> 00:05:23,052
I have
an art‐history degree.

113
00:05:23,052 --> 00:05:25,012
I'm not a friggin'
handyman!

114
00:05:25,012 --> 00:05:28,474
Ugh. This is gonna end up
costing us twice as much now.

115
00:05:28,474 --> 00:05:30,434
Eric: Hey, neighbors!
What's Don ‐‐

116
00:05:30,434 --> 00:05:33,646
Hey! Don!
You need a hand?!

117
00:05:33,646 --> 00:05:35,606
Looks like you need
a pipe wrench!

118
00:05:35,606 --> 00:05:37,233
Dad monkey: I'm fine, Eric,
but thanks!

119
00:05:37,233 --> 00:05:39,026
I‐It's under control!

120
00:05:39,026 --> 00:05:40,611
[Softly] Hey, Siri.
[ Beeping ]

121
00:05:40,611 --> 00:05:42,530
Call handyman.

122
00:05:42,530 --> 00:05:48,202
♪♪

123
00:05:48,202 --> 00:05:51,664
Mirren: While working with
one's hands is a noble pursuit,

124
00:05:51,664 --> 00:05:55,167
there are those,
both human and animal,

125
00:05:55,167 --> 00:05:57,670
who can coast
solely on their looks...

126
00:05:59,422 --> 00:06:02,967
...as we shall see on a visit
to the island of Madagascar

127
00:06:02,967 --> 00:06:07,680
to meet the fetching
sifaka lemur.

128
00:06:07,680 --> 00:06:09,432
[ EDM music plays ]

129
00:06:09,432 --> 00:06:10,725
Photographer: [French accent]
Models aren't born.

130
00:06:10,725 --> 00:06:12,518
They're made!

131
00:06:12,518 --> 00:06:14,729
Once in a blue moon,
you capture a model

132
00:06:14,729 --> 00:06:18,232
that defines beauty, style,
and <i>je ne sais quoi.</i>

133
00:06:18,232 --> 00:06:20,735
He...is...Serge!

134
00:06:20,735 --> 00:06:25,781
♪♪

135
00:06:25,781 --> 00:06:27,325
Temperamental? Yes.

136
00:06:27,325 --> 00:06:29,327
Serge:
Unh! I'm starving!

137
00:06:29,327 --> 00:06:31,704
But it is what you get
when you work with living art!

138
00:06:31,704 --> 00:06:35,583
Hey, everybody! I'm Serge!
And I'm a model! Gah!

139
00:06:35,583 --> 00:06:38,753
Oh. Okay. Uh, that's great.
You look great, Serge!

140
00:06:38,753 --> 00:06:40,463
But less of the talking.

141
00:06:40,463 --> 00:06:42,465
Show me how much
you love nature.

142
00:06:42,465 --> 00:06:44,759
Okay. I'll lick the tree.
I guess!

143
00:06:44,759 --> 00:06:46,969
[ Lips smacking ]

144
00:06:46,969 --> 00:06:49,972
Yes. More of that.
You love that tree, don't you?

145
00:06:49,972 --> 00:06:51,474
[ Camera shutter clicks ]
I love you, tree. Yes.

146
00:06:51,474 --> 00:06:54,602
Yes! Show me!
Love that tree!

147
00:06:54,602 --> 00:06:57,355
You are a sexy mistress
of nature!

148
00:06:57,355 --> 00:07:00,149
Keep going!
You are on fire!

149
00:07:00,149 --> 00:07:02,860
Look! I can almost turn my head
all the way around!

150
00:07:02,860 --> 00:07:04,528
[ Grunting ] Ow!

151
00:07:04,528 --> 00:07:06,238
No, no.

152
00:07:06,238 --> 00:07:09,075
Serge should be seen...
and not heard!

153
00:07:09,075 --> 00:07:11,160
Okay.
I'll be real quiet then!!

154
00:07:11,160 --> 00:07:13,663
Do you hear me?!
I'LL BE REAL QUIET NOW!!

155
00:07:13,663 --> 00:07:17,083
Ugh. Looks like a million bucks,
but, boy, is this guy dumb.

156
00:07:17,083 --> 00:07:19,168
Yes! That's it!
Give me what I need!

157
00:07:22,546 --> 00:07:25,383
♪♪

158
00:07:25,383 --> 00:07:28,302
Mirren: Many animals are
not blessed with a partner ‐‐

159
00:07:28,302 --> 00:07:31,472
one who can serve
as an inspirational muse

160
00:07:31,472 --> 00:07:33,516
or a hunting companion

161
00:07:33,516 --> 00:07:37,436
or just a good hang
you can crack a few beers with.

162
00:07:37,436 --> 00:07:39,605
Solitary creatures must survive

163
00:07:39,605 --> 00:07:43,401
by relying on their own
unique abilities...

164
00:07:43,401 --> 00:07:47,530
especially in the lonely depths
of the mighty ocean.

165
00:07:47,530 --> 00:07:49,365
[ Twinkling ]

166
00:07:49,365 --> 00:07:52,868
Sea fairy: It is I,
the mystical sea fairy..

167
00:07:52,868 --> 00:07:55,538
who only visits
but once a century!

168
00:07:55,538 --> 00:07:58,999
Aren't I <i>so</i> very beautiful?!

169
00:07:58,999 --> 00:08:02,837
Now, I'm ready to grant
your greatest wishes!

170
00:08:02,837 --> 00:08:04,755
Is anyone...?

171
00:08:04,755 --> 00:08:07,216
Nobody's here.

172
00:08:07,216 --> 00:08:09,135
I guess 2021 is going great.

173
00:08:09,135 --> 00:08:11,095
No one needs a wish granted.

174
00:08:11,095 --> 00:08:14,348
A hundred short years ago,
people were stoked to see me,

175
00:08:14,348 --> 00:08:16,726
wishing for stuff
left and right.

176
00:08:16,726 --> 00:08:20,187
Welp. I guess, uh ‐‐ I guess
I'll just come back...later.

177
00:08:21,397 --> 00:08:24,483
♪♪

178
00:08:24,483 --> 00:08:27,737
Mirren: Not all creatures
toil in obscurity.

179
00:08:27,737 --> 00:08:30,906
There are those who exist
to make their presence known.

180
00:08:30,906 --> 00:08:34,952
Yes, another life lesson
our animal friends can impart

181
00:08:34,952 --> 00:08:38,539
is the value in drawing
attention to oneself.

182
00:08:38,539 --> 00:08:40,458
Unless, of course,
you're an antelope

183
00:08:40,458 --> 00:08:43,252
and most of your day is spent
trying not to get eaten.

184
00:08:43,252 --> 00:08:46,380
♪♪

185
00:08:46,380 --> 00:08:49,592
But, still,
there are the bold ones,

186
00:08:49,592 --> 00:08:53,262
the brazen souls who dare
to stand out from the crowd...

187
00:08:53,262 --> 00:08:56,891
like these socially cunning
Japanese squirrels,

188
00:08:56,891 --> 00:09:00,811
who rule their corner
of the Aokigahara Forest.

189
00:09:03,147 --> 00:09:05,149
Narrator: And, now,
grab a rainwater martini

190
00:09:05,149 --> 00:09:06,734
and join the ladies of

191
00:09:06,734 --> 00:09:09,779
"The Real Housewives
of the Forest Biome."

192
00:09:09,779 --> 00:09:12,239
Squirrel #1: Hey, Bev!
Squirrel #2: Yes, dah‐ling.

193
00:09:12,239 --> 00:09:13,741
Do you think I went
a little overboard

194
00:09:13,741 --> 00:09:15,493
on my cheeks this time?

195
00:09:15,493 --> 00:09:17,703
Don't be silly!
They're perfect!

196
00:09:17,703 --> 00:09:19,914
Squirrel #3:
Hey, Bev, what about me?

197
00:09:19,914 --> 00:09:22,166
You couldn't look better
if you tried.

198
00:09:22,166 --> 00:09:24,251
Aww! You mean it?

199
00:09:24,251 --> 00:09:27,838
I swear on my firstborn.
And she's the <i>normal</i> one.

200
00:09:27,838 --> 00:09:30,466
[ All laugh ]

201
00:09:30,466 --> 00:09:33,094
Bev, when are you getting
<i>your</i> cheeks filled?

202
00:09:33,094 --> 00:09:37,181
Why, I'm doing it
right now.

203
00:09:37,181 --> 00:09:39,016
Young squirrel:
Excuse me, ma'am?

204
00:09:39,016 --> 00:09:41,060
Did you just
call me "ma'am"?

205
00:09:41,060 --> 00:09:43,395
[ Gasps ]
Squirrel #3: Oh, no, girl.

206
00:09:43,395 --> 00:09:45,481
Young squirrel:
Yeah, do you know where
the nearest restroom is?

207
00:09:45,481 --> 00:09:47,650
Oh, and now you assume
I work here?

208
00:09:47,650 --> 00:09:49,443
[ Gasps ]

209
00:09:49,443 --> 00:09:50,778
Squirrel #3: Ooh! That's
strike two. Careful, now.

210
00:09:50,778 --> 00:09:52,571
Young squirrel:
I guess I wasn't thinking.

211
00:09:52,571 --> 00:09:55,783
Exactly! Now get your tight fur
out of my sight...

212
00:09:55,783 --> 00:09:57,409
Okay, okay. Geez.

213
00:09:57,409 --> 00:09:59,370
...before I lose my nuts!

214
00:10:05,042 --> 00:10:10,756
♪♪

215
00:10:10,756 --> 00:10:13,092
Mirren: We can learn so much
from the inhabitants

216
00:10:13,092 --> 00:10:16,387
of the animal kingdom.

217
00:10:16,387 --> 00:10:20,141
Wisdom can be gleaned
from the noble lion...

218
00:10:20,141 --> 00:10:23,018
the majestic hermit crab...

219
00:10:23,018 --> 00:10:25,604
and elephants,
who I honestly think

220
00:10:25,604 --> 00:10:28,023
are kind of overrated, actually.

221
00:10:28,023 --> 00:10:30,985
Ohh! What about these guys?!

222
00:10:30,985 --> 00:10:33,195
♪♪

223
00:10:33,195 --> 00:10:34,780
Jerr‐‐
Where's my producer, Jerry?

224
00:10:34,780 --> 00:10:35,990
Jerry:
<i>Uh, yes, Dame Helen?</i>

225
00:10:35,990 --> 00:10:37,408
What is this animal?

226
00:10:37,408 --> 00:10:39,493
What is it?
Some kind of raccoon cat?

227
00:10:39,493 --> 00:10:40,911
<i>Those are, uh...</i>

228
00:10:40,911 --> 00:10:42,413
[ <i>Papers shuffling</i> ]

229
00:10:42,413 --> 00:10:43,664
<i>...coatis.</i>

230
00:10:43,664 --> 00:10:46,417
Hmm! Coatis.

231
00:10:46,417 --> 00:10:48,377
Bring me one. I want one.

232
00:10:48,377 --> 00:10:52,089
<i>Well, they're a‐a wild animal</i>
<i>a‐and protected, I think.</i>

233
00:10:52,089 --> 00:10:53,966
Oh, okay.

234
00:10:53,966 --> 00:10:56,177
Then put me down
for a couple of chipmunks

235
00:10:56,177 --> 00:10:59,180
or ground squirrels till
we get this coati thing sorted.

236
00:10:59,180 --> 00:11:00,514
<i>You got it.</i>

237
00:11:00,514 --> 00:11:04,476
Thank you, Jerry!
You're the best.

238
00:11:04,476 --> 00:11:07,688
I know; I don't tell you that
enough, do I?

239
00:11:07,688 --> 00:11:12,484
And therein lies another
vital lesson we can glean.

240
00:11:12,484 --> 00:11:15,613
Careful communication
is vitally important,

241
00:11:15,613 --> 00:11:17,865
especially in the wild.

242
00:11:17,865 --> 00:11:20,618
Just ask
the North American pika,

243
00:11:20,618 --> 00:11:24,079
who are as social
as they are skittish.

244
00:11:26,081 --> 00:11:28,083
Pika wife: Hey, hon?
Pika: Yeah?

245
00:11:28,083 --> 00:11:29,627
Know what I was thinking
the other day?

246
00:11:29,627 --> 00:11:31,212
Totally!

247
00:11:31,212 --> 00:11:32,588
I can't believe
that tomorrow's

248
00:11:32,588 --> 00:11:34,590
already our seven‐year
anniversary!

249
00:11:34,590 --> 00:11:38,052
Crazy, right?
Wait. Seven years?

250
00:11:38,052 --> 00:11:40,596
Oh, God! Not again!

251
00:11:40,596 --> 00:11:43,098
[ Frantic music plays ]

252
00:11:43,098 --> 00:11:45,684
I'll take this.
And this.

253
00:11:45,684 --> 00:11:47,186
Ooh, and this.

254
00:11:47,186 --> 00:11:49,480
Weasel:
Hey! My begonias!

255
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:52,483
[Muffled] Sorry, Steve.
Need these more than you!

256
00:11:52,483 --> 00:11:54,693
♪♪

257
00:11:54,693 --> 00:11:56,862
Boobie husband:
There goes Harold again.

258
00:11:56,862 --> 00:11:59,698
Boobie wife: Yeah, I wonder what
he did to Jeannie <i>this</i> time.

259
00:11:59,698 --> 00:12:01,951
Boobie husband:
Poor guy can't win.

260
00:12:03,327 --> 00:12:04,912
[ Panting ]

261
00:12:04,912 --> 00:12:07,498
Happy seventh anniversary,
sweetheart! Heh‐heh!

262
00:12:07,498 --> 00:12:09,917
Harold, I was talking
about it being seven years

263
00:12:09,917 --> 00:12:11,710
since we remodeled
our bathroom.

264
00:12:11,710 --> 00:12:14,797
Oh. Uh, y‐yeah.
Heh. I knew that.

265
00:12:14,797 --> 00:12:17,007
So should I find a vase
for these or...?

266
00:12:17,007 --> 00:12:20,302
And we've been married for
thirteen years, not seven.

267
00:12:20,302 --> 00:12:22,054
Yep. Got it.

268
00:12:22,054 --> 00:12:26,100
♪♪

269
00:12:26,100 --> 00:12:27,768
Mirren:
Our animal friends

270
00:12:27,768 --> 00:12:31,563
mirror our own romantic pursuits
back at us.

271
00:12:31,563 --> 00:12:35,484
We recognize, in their
wild, horny fumblings,

272
00:12:35,484 --> 00:12:38,112
ourselves...

273
00:12:38,112 --> 00:12:41,865
and we see
the same insecurities...

274
00:12:41,865 --> 00:12:45,369
foibles, and sweaty desperation

275
00:12:45,369 --> 00:12:48,914
that often accompany
our search toward...

276
00:12:48,914 --> 00:12:51,333
you know, hooking up,

277
00:12:51,333 --> 00:12:54,295
bumping uglies, what‐have‐you.

278
00:12:54,295 --> 00:12:56,964
And our closest animal relative,

279
00:12:56,964 --> 00:12:59,717
the chimpanzee
of the African Congo,

280
00:12:59,717 --> 00:13:03,012
knows full well
that the art of seduction

281
00:13:03,012 --> 00:13:06,473
can be difficult to master.

282
00:13:06,473 --> 00:13:11,770
♪♪

283
00:13:11,770 --> 00:13:17,234
♪♪

284
00:13:17,234 --> 00:13:19,028
Male chimp: But soft!

285
00:13:19,028 --> 00:13:21,280
What light through
yonder window breaks?

286
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:24,366
It is the east.
And Juliet is the sun.

287
00:13:24,366 --> 00:13:26,243
Female chimp: Aye, me.

288
00:13:26,243 --> 00:13:27,745
She speaks!

289
00:13:27,745 --> 00:13:30,581
Her eye discourses.
I will answer it.

290
00:13:30,581 --> 00:13:32,791
[ Clears throat ]

291
00:13:32,791 --> 00:13:36,045
Heh heh heh.
Hiiiiiiii! Ehh...

292
00:13:36,045 --> 00:13:38,213
What? Who said that?

293
00:13:38,213 --> 00:13:41,550
Meeee! Heh!
It's me! I said that!

294
00:13:41,550 --> 00:13:43,552
I've been watching you
on your balcony

295
00:13:43,552 --> 00:13:45,012
from down here. Hi!

296
00:13:45,012 --> 00:13:47,264
Ugh! Scram, creep!

297
00:13:47,264 --> 00:13:50,768
Okay. Fair enough.
Bye‐eee!

298
00:13:50,768 --> 00:13:52,644
[ Water bubbling ]

299
00:13:52,644 --> 00:13:54,188
[ Twinkling ]

300
00:13:54,188 --> 00:13:56,190
Sea fairy: 'Tis I! Again!

301
00:13:56,190 --> 00:13:59,401
The mystical wish‐granting
sea fairy. From earlier?

302
00:13:59,401 --> 00:14:01,653
No? Well...

303
00:14:01,653 --> 00:14:03,906
I'm still just...
swimming around,

304
00:14:03,906 --> 00:14:06,533
looking for anyone
who might have a wish.

305
00:14:06,533 --> 00:14:08,535
Nobody? Really?

306
00:14:08,535 --> 00:14:10,412
Maybe it's because
I'm four miles underneath

307
00:14:10,412 --> 00:14:12,039
the surface of the ocean.

308
00:14:12,039 --> 00:14:14,333
You know,
when I appeared last century,

309
00:14:14,333 --> 00:14:16,251
I took the form
of a majestic glowing fox

310
00:14:16,251 --> 00:14:18,253
that wandered from town to town.

311
00:14:18,253 --> 00:14:22,299
This time, I'm a slug floating
in the middle of the ocean.

312
00:14:22,299 --> 00:14:24,426
Not the best choice
in terms of foot traffic, yes.

313
00:14:24,426 --> 00:14:25,886
That's on me.

314
00:14:25,886 --> 00:14:27,930
Still, you'd think
there'd be at least

315
00:14:27,930 --> 00:14:30,641
some blobfish out there wishing
they didn't look so stupid.

316
00:14:30,641 --> 00:14:32,309
[ Laughs ]

317
00:14:32,309 --> 00:14:34,269
Okay, that was unprofessional
of me.

318
00:14:34,269 --> 00:14:35,979
Still? Nobody?

319
00:14:35,979 --> 00:14:37,523
COME ON!!

320
00:14:37,523 --> 00:14:39,024
Well, joke's on you people.

321
00:14:39,024 --> 00:14:41,026
'Cause I can live forever.

322
00:14:41,026 --> 00:14:44,113
And next time I come back,
you'll all be long dead!

323
00:14:44,113 --> 00:14:45,989
So long, [bleep]!

324
00:14:47,825 --> 00:14:53,997
♪♪

325
00:14:53,997 --> 00:15:00,462
♪♪

326
00:15:00,462 --> 00:15:05,342
Mirren: Life in the wild,
like our human existence,

327
00:15:05,342 --> 00:15:07,845
is marked by unpredictability...

328
00:15:10,764 --> 00:15:14,143
...shadowy dangers...

329
00:15:14,143 --> 00:15:17,146
and the grim specter of fright.

330
00:15:17,146 --> 00:15:19,273
[ Laughs evilly ]

331
00:15:19,273 --> 00:15:21,233
[ Laughing joyously ]

332
00:15:21,233 --> 00:15:23,986
Oh, sorry. I just thought
of something funny.

333
00:15:26,321 --> 00:15:29,116
Anyway, perhaps you, too,
have encountered

334
00:15:29,116 --> 00:15:31,785
one of the most challenging
of life's lessons ‐‐

335
00:15:31,785 --> 00:15:34,163
how to face one's fears.

336
00:15:40,377 --> 00:15:41,837
[ Suspenseful music plays ]

337
00:15:41,837 --> 00:15:44,298
Frog: Okay. Okay.
You can do this, Jake.

338
00:15:44,298 --> 00:15:46,383
I‐It's just the high dive.

339
00:15:46,383 --> 00:15:49,011
A v‐v‐v‐very high dive.

340
00:15:49,011 --> 00:15:51,013
Snake: Hey, Jake.
Jussst jump already.

341
00:15:51,013 --> 00:15:52,723
What are you waiting for?

342
00:15:52,723 --> 00:15:54,600
Frog:
I will! I'll jump!

343
00:15:54,600 --> 00:15:56,435
[Nervously]
On my own time.

344
00:15:56,435 --> 00:15:58,395
I'll jump. Like now.

345
00:15:58,395 --> 00:16:00,397
In three, two...

346
00:16:00,397 --> 00:16:02,858
Ohh, boy.
Okay. Come on.

347
00:16:02,858 --> 00:16:04,985
Just one little jump,
and you'll prove to your friend

348
00:16:04,985 --> 00:16:06,862
that you're not afraid
of heights!

349
00:16:06,862 --> 00:16:10,365
[ Snake chanting ]
Ju‐ump! Ju‐ump! Ju‐ump!

350
00:16:10,365 --> 00:16:13,035
Stheriously,
don't be such a chicken!

351
00:16:13,035 --> 00:16:14,828
Have you always
had that lisp?

352
00:16:14,828 --> 00:16:17,956
I'm trying Invithalign.
That'th it. I'm gonna push you!

353
00:16:17,956 --> 00:16:19,875
What?! Push me?!
Don't!

354
00:16:19,875 --> 00:16:22,211
Fine. I'll just...

355
00:16:22,211 --> 00:16:25,214
j‐u‐u‐u‐u‐u‐u‐u‐u‐ump!

356
00:16:25,214 --> 00:16:27,883
Oh, wow! He did it!

357
00:16:27,883 --> 00:16:29,801
[ Thud ]
Ow! Ugh!

358
00:16:29,801 --> 00:16:31,803
Gah! Unh!

359
00:16:31,803 --> 00:16:33,555
[ Thud ]

360
00:16:33,555 --> 00:16:38,060
Sthorry. I forgot
they drained the pool.

361
00:16:38,060 --> 00:16:41,063
♪♪

362
00:16:41,063 --> 00:16:43,732
Mirren: One of the key lessons
to survival in the wild

363
00:16:43,732 --> 00:16:47,110
is simple awareness.

364
00:16:47,110 --> 00:16:48,987
Is that animal
lurking in the shadows

365
00:16:48,987 --> 00:16:52,407
a friend or a predator?

366
00:16:52,407 --> 00:16:55,577
Is it safe to drink
from this stream?

367
00:16:55,577 --> 00:16:59,373
And where the hell
did I park my car?

368
00:16:59,373 --> 00:17:02,876
In short, one must learn
to be always aware

369
00:17:02,876 --> 00:17:05,170
of one's surroundings.

370
00:17:05,170 --> 00:17:07,172
[ Game‐show jingle plays ]

371
00:17:07,172 --> 00:17:10,008
Game‐show host: And, now,
the brand‐new game show

372
00:17:10,008 --> 00:17:12,135
everyone is howling about!

373
00:17:12,135 --> 00:17:14,304
It's time for...

374
00:17:14,304 --> 00:17:17,224
Studio audience:
Wolf! Or! Rock!

375
00:17:17,224 --> 00:17:19,184
Game‐show host:
Let's meet tonight's contestant!

376
00:17:19,184 --> 00:17:22,980
Rich: Yeah, I'm Rich, a retiree
from Scottsdale, Arizona.

377
00:17:22,980 --> 00:17:25,732
Okay, Rich.
Let's play the game.

378
00:17:25,732 --> 00:17:27,067
Do you see...

379
00:17:27,067 --> 00:17:30,279
a wolf...or a rock?

380
00:17:30,279 --> 00:17:31,863
I'm ready to answer.

381
00:17:31,863 --> 00:17:33,323
Wait till you hear
the buzzer.

382
00:17:33,323 --> 00:17:34,700
Yeah, but I'm ready
to answer now.

383
00:17:34,700 --> 00:17:36,702
Shh! Just...quiet.

384
00:17:36,702 --> 00:17:38,370
[ Buzzer ]

385
00:17:38,370 --> 00:17:42,457
Now, Rich, what did you see?
A wolf or a rock?

386
00:17:42,457 --> 00:17:44,960
Yeah, it's a wolf.
Obviously.

387
00:17:44,960 --> 00:17:47,671
And the answer is ‐‐
Audience?

388
00:17:47,671 --> 00:17:49,339
Studio audience: Rock!
[ Bell dinging ]

389
00:17:49,339 --> 00:17:50,716
Wait. What?!
Wait a minute!

390
00:17:50,716 --> 00:17:52,384
And that's
all the time we have.

391
00:17:52,384 --> 00:17:54,136
Seriously,
what the [bleep]?

392
00:17:54,136 --> 00:17:58,223
Tune in next week for another
enthralling episode of...

393
00:17:58,223 --> 00:18:00,309
Studio audience:
Wolf! Or! Rock!

394
00:18:04,438 --> 00:18:11,111
♪♪

395
00:18:11,111 --> 00:18:12,821
[ Sensual music plays ]

396
00:18:12,821 --> 00:18:15,991
Amber:
Hi, guys. It's Amber.

397
00:18:15,991 --> 00:18:19,578
And welcome to
my OnlyFins Page.

398
00:18:19,578 --> 00:18:22,956
Now, who wants to see me

399
00:18:22,956 --> 00:18:26,251
eat...this...algae?

400
00:18:27,961 --> 00:18:29,963
[ Dramatic music plays ]

401
00:18:29,963 --> 00:18:35,761
♪♪

402
00:18:35,761 --> 00:18:39,848
Mirren: As we pierce the veil
of the animal kingdom

403
00:18:39,848 --> 00:18:44,394
and behold the wondrous
creatures who reside within,

404
00:18:44,394 --> 00:18:48,398
we are struck
by their stories...

405
00:18:48,398 --> 00:18:52,027
and, in some cases,
their body hair...

406
00:18:52,027 --> 00:18:56,573
and we uncover the universal
life lessons within.

407
00:18:56,573 --> 00:19:01,912
Animals, like us, must learn
the value of hard work...

408
00:19:01,912 --> 00:19:04,539
the importance
of conquering their fears...

409
00:19:04,539 --> 00:19:07,501
and the value of persistence.

410
00:19:07,501 --> 00:19:10,337
For those with intricate
social structures,

411
00:19:10,337 --> 00:19:13,465
like the Virunga mountain
gorillas of East Africa,

412
00:19:13,465 --> 00:19:16,218
there can be great pressure
to prove oneself.

413
00:19:22,599 --> 00:19:24,267
Casting assistant: Gorilla
auditioning for role of Gorilla.

414
00:19:24,267 --> 00:19:26,186
Take 1.
[ Clapboard snaps ]

415
00:19:26,186 --> 00:19:28,271
Gorilla: Can't believe I need
to audition, but whatever.

416
00:19:28,271 --> 00:19:30,732
[ Chuckles ]
How 'bout a little swing?

417
00:19:30,732 --> 00:19:32,609
I did this on
"Planet of the Apes."

418
00:19:32,609 --> 00:19:34,152
It's on my résumé.

419
00:19:34,152 --> 00:19:37,322
You probably remember
"Ooh‐ooh, ahh‐ahh!"

420
00:19:37,322 --> 00:19:38,824
Yeah, that's a little bit
of my monologue

421
00:19:38,824 --> 00:19:41,451
from a little film called
"Kong: Skull Island."

422
00:19:41,451 --> 00:19:43,870
Lot of college dudes
still quote that.

423
00:19:43,870 --> 00:19:45,831
Casting assistant: Gorilla
auditioning for role of Gorilla.

424
00:19:45,831 --> 00:19:47,708
Take 2.
[ Clapboard snaps ]

425
00:19:47,708 --> 00:19:49,543
Gorilla: Of course I can.
I'm professionally trained.

426
00:19:49,543 --> 00:19:53,255
Lesson one ‐‐ [Grunts]
no matter how hard ‐‐ unh ‐‐

427
00:19:53,255 --> 00:19:54,923
[Muffled]
...make it look easy.

428
00:19:54,923 --> 00:19:56,466
[ Spits ]

429
00:19:56,466 --> 00:19:59,803
And that's what you call
working with props.

430
00:19:59,803 --> 00:20:01,263
Casting assistant: Gorilla
auditioning for role of Gorilla.

431
00:20:01,263 --> 00:20:02,514
Take 3.
[ Clapboard snaps ]

432
00:20:02,514 --> 00:20:04,474
Gorilla:
Hey‐oh! One‐handed.

433
00:20:04,474 --> 00:20:06,893
Heh. That's some pro [bleep]
right there.

434
00:20:06,893 --> 00:20:09,312
Ope! One hand again. Ha‐ha!

435
00:20:09,312 --> 00:20:10,897
I should be a household name.

436
00:20:10,897 --> 00:20:14,484
Heyyy!
Ooh‐ooh, ahh‐ahh, right? Ha‐ha!

437
00:20:14,484 --> 00:20:16,611
Our grandkids will be quoting
that when we're both dead.

438
00:20:16,611 --> 00:20:19,030
By the way,
I also do my own...

439
00:20:19,030 --> 00:20:20,198
[ Branch snaps ]
...st‐u‐u‐u‐unts!

440
00:20:20,198 --> 00:20:21,491
[ Thud ]

441
00:20:21,491 --> 00:20:26,288
♪♪

442
00:20:26,288 --> 00:20:28,915
Mirren: We depart
the treetops of the lowlands

443
00:20:28,915 --> 00:20:31,960
to once again return
to the haunting majesty

444
00:20:31,960 --> 00:20:34,129
of the ocean floor,

445
00:20:34,129 --> 00:20:39,634
where we check in one last time
with an old friend.

446
00:20:39,634 --> 00:20:40,761
[ Twinkling ]

447
00:20:40,761 --> 00:20:43,054
Sea fairy: 'Tis I. Yep.

448
00:20:43,054 --> 00:20:44,681
The mystical sea fairy.

449
00:20:44,681 --> 00:20:46,266
Still here.

450
00:20:46,266 --> 00:20:49,519
[ Sighs heavily ]
Seriously. What is up?

451
00:20:49,519 --> 00:20:52,522
Everyone keeps swimming by.
Nobody wants a wish.

452
00:20:52,522 --> 00:20:55,066
Acting like <i>I'm</i> the [bleep].

453
00:20:55,066 --> 00:20:59,112
A starfish just gave me
the finger like five times!

454
00:20:59,112 --> 00:21:00,947
How often do you come across

455
00:21:00,947 --> 00:21:03,658
a magical, wish‐granting
sea fairy?

456
00:21:03,658 --> 00:21:05,535
Come on!

457
00:21:05,535 --> 00:21:08,079
I even paid for a whole bunch
of Instagram ads.

458
00:21:08,079 --> 00:21:10,123
Nothing. Ugh!

459
00:21:10,123 --> 00:21:12,501
My dad was right. I should
have gone to law school.

460
00:21:12,501 --> 00:21:14,294
[ Sobbing ]

461
00:21:14,294 --> 00:21:22,135
♪♪

462
00:21:22,135 --> 00:21:25,514
Mirren: The world of nature
is not merely one of splendor...

463
00:21:25,514 --> 00:21:28,141
♪♪

464
00:21:28,141 --> 00:21:29,601
...grandeur...

465
00:21:29,601 --> 00:21:32,270
♪♪

466
00:21:32,270 --> 00:21:36,733
...and endless glimpses
of windswept vistas.

467
00:21:36,733 --> 00:21:39,319
Although, sure,
it's got a buttload of those.

468
00:21:39,319 --> 00:21:41,196
♪♪

469
00:21:41,196 --> 00:21:45,492
Rather, this world can often
embody two ideas at once.

470
00:21:45,492 --> 00:21:47,202
♪♪

471
00:21:47,202 --> 00:21:50,121
Peril and mischief...

472
00:21:50,121 --> 00:21:53,917
beauty and absurdity...

473
00:21:53,917 --> 00:21:59,339
and, like, kind of gross bugs
and cute baby bears.

474
00:21:59,339 --> 00:22:03,468
And all of them speak
to the lessons of life...

475
00:22:03,468 --> 00:22:05,887
when nature calls.

476
00:22:05,887 --> 00:22:09,724
♪♪

477
00:22:09,724 --> 00:22:12,477
Stan Eiseberg:
Are you tired of clambering
up steep, slippery inclines

478
00:22:12,477 --> 00:22:14,813
only to fall back down
like a clumsy fool?

479
00:22:14,813 --> 00:22:16,523
[ Penguin squawks ]

480
00:22:16,523 --> 00:22:18,358
Are you sick and tired
of fighting against gravity

481
00:22:18,358 --> 00:22:20,735
and your own inability
to evolve?

482
00:22:20,735 --> 00:22:22,612
Penguin: Whoopsie!
Stan Eiseberg:
Have you slid down

483
00:22:22,612 --> 00:22:25,365
into the frigid arctic waters
and thought to yourself,

484
00:22:25,365 --> 00:22:26,950
"There's gotta be a better way"?

485
00:22:26,950 --> 00:22:29,160
Well, friends, there is.

486
00:22:29,160 --> 00:22:31,079
Hi. I'm Stan Eiseberg,

487
00:22:31,079 --> 00:22:33,123
for Eiseberg's
Penguin Stairs.

488
00:22:33,123 --> 00:22:35,333
For years, climbing
has been the bane

489
00:22:35,333 --> 00:22:36,877
of penguin
existence.

490
00:22:36,877 --> 00:22:38,587
Our silly little feet
can't grip,

491
00:22:38,587 --> 00:22:40,630
and I don't even think
we have knees.

492
00:22:40,630 --> 00:22:44,009
I try not to dwell on it.
It's pretty upsetting.

493
00:22:44,009 --> 00:22:47,012
But, now, with my patented
stair technology,

494
00:22:47,012 --> 00:22:50,557
you can take the first step
into a brighter future,

495
00:22:50,557 --> 00:22:52,809
one where you're not flailing
like a buffoon

496
00:22:52,809 --> 00:22:55,854
and sliding helplessly into
the mouth of a hungry orca.

497
00:22:55,854 --> 00:22:57,772
So stop being nature's
little clown,

498
00:22:57,772 --> 00:23:01,276
always falling over and soiling
your fancy little tuxedo.

499
00:23:01,276 --> 00:23:04,362
You're a penguin. Be proud.

500
00:23:04,362 --> 00:23:06,573
